This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements. 
.
When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉
.
Shout out to @benlustigphysiotherapy for sharing this exercise with me & @edpilgrimdpt for being my model athlete today. Also shout out to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body & @olychad for his lifting demos.

During Luke’s injury rehab with me, we ran into a pretty significant limitation in ankle mobility. Now we were definitely seeing some progress with banded joint mobilizations, stretching and soft tissue work with rolling, but he was still a little off balance in his bottom squat position.📝
.
Now when I see problems like this – we often look at the ankle joint  especially the motion of knee moving over the toe – a motion called dorsiflexion – but we need to also look at the motions that occur in other planes like rotation and glide.✅
.
I assessed his lateral shin motion with this movement. Clearly very different on his injury side. This prompted me to test his tibial rotation and as you can see he has much less rotation on his injured side.📝
.
I suggested he use this banded drill. With the band placed under the base of his 1st toe, he tensioned the band and drove his knee out to the side – feeling his glutes working hard and held for 10”. Now if you don’t keep a stable foot during this motion the band will snap out from under your foot.❌ .
We also worked on trying to improve lateral tibial glide, holding the foot down in place and pushing the knee to the side and holding for a few seconds. After performing those you can see a huge difference in ankle mobility.🙌🏼 .
So the next week when we were squatting, I noted he was a little off balance in his bottom position – with the bar shooting out over his toes. We did one more set of tibial rotation drills and the very next see you can see a large difference – now more balanced and able to sit down with the bar over his mid foot.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @thelukemeredith for putting in the hard work during rehab, you're doing such great work man. Also thank you to @3d4medical with the compete anatomy app for the visual of the body today. .

Learning this set up is also a very important part of the rehab process when returning from back pain (like @superchuckcw is shown here performing). This is because many who develop back pain when deadlifting have very strong backs but fail to control the strength they do have and coordinate it with the hips. 
.
These tips are things I have picked up from giants who have come before me like @eddycoan, @briancarroll1306 & @backfitpro. 
.

Notice the shift in Heather's deadlift set up which causes her to pull off balance and twist slightly during this lift. I started this days assessment by looking at her hip mobility on both sides. Her right side checked out well, however when I brought her leg up to her chest on the left side she noticed a little pinching pain in the front of the hip joint that worsened as I brought the knee across her body. 📝
.
This test showed she was dealing with a hip impingement, where the femur was running into the front side of the hip socket and creating a pinching pain in the front of the hip. This means her unbalanced set up and pull was because she was shifting and twisting away from the impingement. 📝
.
To make some more room for the femur within the hip socket we worked on some banded joint mobilizations pulling laterally on the hip. I had her lean forward for a few seconds while pushing the hip into the prior restriction before coming out, driving the knee wide and squeezing her lateral glutes for 10 reps total. We then attempted the hip airplane unassisted.✅
.
After 1 week of using these exercises you can see a huge improvement in her bottom set position, here it is compared to her prior week. This allowed her to then perform a more balanced and optimal pull.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @heathaaarey for putting in the hard work to fix these movement issues and to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body in todays post🙏🏼

Squatting all comes down to balance. For some people the knees will HAVE to move forward past the toes in order to descend to a great depth and maintain balance. For others, the knees wont pass the knees, and that's okay too as long as they are staying balanced. When dealing with knee pain, it is often a good idea to limit the amount of knee-over-toe translation as pushing this forward motion can many times create more pain. Doing so can allow us to take stress of the symptomatic joint and address the cause of pain (by looking at mobility problems at the hips/ankles and/or stability issues). Context matters. 
.

node.text:
Early in my career as a physical therapist, it was common to prescribe certain stretches (like pulling your knees to your chest while lying on your back) as an exercise for many with low back pain. At the time this exercise made sense. Those who had difficulty standing for long periods or lying flat on their back often felt better when in a flexed position. Many who complained of feeling stiff and painful in their low back had instant relief of their symptoms after performing a few of these stretches.🤔
.
However, I realized (after reading and studying from Dr. Stuart McGill @backfitpro) that this relief is only a temporary relief for most. When you stretch your low back, you are stimulating the stretch receptors deep inside the muscles that give the perception of pain relief and the feeling of less stiffness.🤯
.
In fact, most of the muscle pain and stiffness you may feel in your back is consequence of a chemical reaction called inflammation that occurs from the real injury often located deeper in the spine (disc bulge, facet irritation, etc). The underlying injury is what causes the secondary contraction or spasm of the surrounding muscles and pain.🤯
.
Unlike other stretches for the low back that can place unwanted stresses on the spine, the cat-camel exercise emphases mobility in a very spine-friendly low load manner. If you'd like to learn more about what I do AFTER the cat-camel, check out the full rest of this video on my YouTube "Quick Tips for Low Back Tweaks.”📲
.
If you’re also dealing with low back pain, it is key to find out your exact movement triggers for pain (as there is no one size fits all treatment). To learn the tests I use to determine your movement diagnosis - check out my blog “how to screen your low back pain” on squatuniversity.com📲
.

If you want to perform the clean & snatch lifts you NEED to be squatting to the greatest depth possible in order to build capacity & comfort in the extreme bottom positions needed for efficient Olympic lifting. Remember the deeper you can catch the bar, the more weight you can get under. For this reason, squatting to “hip crease below the knee” is NOT good enough for preparing the body for the clean & snatch. 
.
If you need help with your squat mobility - 2x Olympian Chad Vaughn @olychad and I just came out with a YouTube video showing a 10 minute squat mobility routine. Be sure to check it out on the SquatU YouTube channel!📲

So you’re trying to improve your lat flexibility with stretches like this or even some soft tissue mobilizations with a foam roller but did you know you can also use an eccentric curl up to help as well?🤔
.
Your lat muscles are the big “V” shaped muscles that run from your low back to your upper arm. Poor flexibility of this muscle will limit how far you can raise your arm over your head – meaning it will affect your ability to show good technique with overhead lifts like the push press or getting your elbows up in a front squat.🙌🏼
.
To perform the eccentric curl up – start with an underhand grip on the bar. Jump to the top position before lowering slowly in about 5 seconds. During this lower your muscles are lengthened under tension which has been shown to help improve flexibility just like stretching.✅✅
.
Besides feeling for improvement in your lifts, you can also gauge your flexibility improvement by performing this wall test with your palms up while grabbing a PVC pipe every week or so.📝
.
If you’d like to learn more ways to improve flexibility of the lats (and the research behind eccentric work for flexibility improvements) check out my blog article “How to improve pec and lat flexibility” on Squatuniversity.com📲
.

node.text:
If you want to enjoy not only your youth but also your FULL LIFE, always make strength training a priority. 
.
The Why: Muscles have a certain capacity to perform work. The larger the capacity, the more reserve they have. Let’s use the biceps as an example. Let’s say your best bicep curl is 100 pounds for 1 RM. If your biceps performed 5 pound curls every minute for 8 hours, it could probably hold out and last. However, what would happen if your best bicep curl was only 20 pounds for 1 RM. Your poor biceps are not going to be able to sustain lifting 5 pounds every minute for 8 hours. Eventually you potentially develop tendonitis, DOMS (delayed onset muscle soreness) or even rhabdomyolysis.
.
Now, let’s switch out the biceps for the full body. If your body can sustain and lift a heavier 1RM, your body will certainly be more resilient to injuries. Standing up and sitting down would be an easier task if you had a strong squat. Taking walks/hikes wouldn’t be such an issue with strong legs/core. Picking anything off the ground is easy with a good deadlift. Pushing a box to a high shelf is easy with a strong press. 
.
The point I’m trying to make and get across is that you should lift heavy every once and a while! Don’t be afraid to challenge yourself to a 1RM or 3RM. Make sure you have an experienced coach or trainer assess your technique before attempting a personal record. Staying in your “comfort zone” is not a bad thing. However, you are selling yourself short by not seeing what your body is capable of and improving your capacity for LIFE. 
.
There have been numerous studies and articles written on how muscle loss and weakness is positively correlated with death and a shorter life span. Strength training when performed correctly and with good programming, will improve core strength, increase muscle mass/power/strength, increase your resiliency to injuries and improve your life expectancy.
.
Remember exercise & proper movement is medicine.

The touchdown progression is my favorite way to slowly improve your single leg squat quality & depth. While not everyone will be capable of a FULL DEPTH pistol squat, we all have the capability to do a quality single leg squat off at least a 12 inch height stack of plates. 
.
The reason this progression is so helpful is that it requires you to focus on control & balance. Holding onto something (like a suspension trainer) may allow you to go deeper with your squat but doesn’t challenge your control & balance. Work on your mobility (especially ankle mobility) and then process your single leg squat without restraints in this manner and it will take you much further in the long run.
.
Remember: crawl, walk, run. The same applies to single leg squats. Start with baby steps and progress with depth as you can under control!
.
Programming: start with 2 sets of 20 reps at a small height. Don’t go up until you can easily master all 20 reps without balance issues. Once you can get to a height of 10 inches, then start to drop reps to sets of 10. 
.
For more, check out my YouTube video “How to get your first pistol squat.”📲

Do you use pauses in your lifts (squats, deadlifts, bench, Olympic lifts)?🤔 If so what is your experience?
.
Adding in pauses can be an excellent variation that can help increase technical capacity in the lifts by teaching you how to maintain positions. Many athletes love to rush too quickly through lifts. By slowing the lift down & adding in pauses in strategic areas we can expose problems in control & work to enhance our ownership of the lift!
.
Example 1: a pause squat in the bottom position for 5-10 seconds. Look at your ability to feel comfortable and balanced in the bottom position & then how you come out - are you balanced on the ascent or do your hips rise too fast (aka the good morning or stripper squat fault)?
.
Example 2: a pause just below or above the knee during a deadlift held for 2-3 seconds. Watch your back angle. Do you feel fatigue in your back (incorrect) or is your core braced and the hips working hard to maintain position?
.
Example 3: a pause in the full standing position after a jerk for 10 seconds. Feel for being in a comfortable locked out position overhead. Are you stable or constantly fighting to keep the bar up?

node.text:
What are your thoughts?🤔 It’s always interesting looking at the comment section of lifting videos. Depending on the lift, sometimes you’ll see many praises or plenty of criticisms for the person’s technique (sometimes both on the same video). 
.
While our goal is always to perfect technique, we are all at different places in our strength journey. Learning the lifts takes years. This is why it’s so important to find a good coach that can help us find sufficient technique to start loading (we don’t need to be perfect to start but we need to move well enough to tolerate the loads you’re going to place on your body. From there we continue to progress as we can). It’s a process that doesn’t happen overnight.
.
The world has enough critics. There’s a big difference between helpful advice & hurtful criticism. If you can’t drop a word of encouragement with a helpful piece of advice in the comments sometimes the best thing is to just keep scrolling.
